CANINE ENTERIC CORONAVIRUS - AUSTRALIA: (CANTERBURY) DOG RACE
*************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 19 Jul 2021 21:04 NZST
Source: Stuff.co.nz [edited]
https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/racing/125799339/greyhound-races-canned-after-dogs-test-positive-for-canine-coronavirus


Three dogs tested positive for canine enteric coronavirus at a meeting in Christchurch on Monday last week [week of 12 Jul 2021].

The discovery meant 6 race meetings had to be cancelled, with the next event scheduled for 26 Jul 2021.

The virus only affects the gastrointestinal system of dogs and is not related to the COVID-19 coronavirus.

Christchurch Greyhound Racing Club manager Tony Music said the dogs at the race meeting where the virus was detected would be isolated. The infected greyhounds have been isolated.

These cancellations will have a "significant" financial impact on the industry. "You can't get those meetings back,'' he said.

"My understanding is that the virus is very contagious, so the safest thing to do was abandon the races."

New Zealand Veterinary Association companion animal veterinary manager Lorelle Barrett said the disease was rare in domestic dogs.

"We tend to see it where there are dogs in higher density kennels. Greyhound kennels would be a typical situation,'' she said. "It is not commonly reported at all in our domestic dog population."

She said clinical signs included diarrhoea and vomiting. "It is quite contagious, but they usually recover quickly."

[Byline: Charlie Gates]

