Communicated by:
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>

["There are 2 forms of canine coronavirus: enteric canine coronavirus (CCoV) and respiratory canine coronavirus (CRCoV). Vaccines protecting against enteric coronavirus infection do not provide protection against the respiratory form of this disease [see ref below].

"The enteric canine coronavirus (CCoV) and respiratory canine coronavirus (CRCoV) are not the same viruses as SARS-CoV-2, which is responsible for the COVID-19 infection. For more information on COVID-19 and pets please visit the CDC website [https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/daily-life-coping/animals.html]

"Transmission
Enteric canine coronavirus is spread through contact with oral secretions or contact with infected feces. Coronaviruses are fairly resistant and can remain infectious for longer periods outdoors at frozen temperatures.

"Clinical signs
- Depression
- Loss of appetite
- Vomiting
- Acute diarrhea
- Yellow to orange diarrhea varying from soft to watery (may also contain blood)
- Fever (occasionally)

"Risk factors
- Young dogs
- Dogs coming from shelters, rescue centers, breeding kennels, or pet stores [and racing conditions, where there are many animals gathered in an area. - Mod.TG]
- Boarding at a kennel or doggie daycare
- Visiting groomers, dog parks, or engaging with other dogs on a daily basis
- Dogs that live in multiple pet homes

Reference
---------
85. https://www.avma.org/resources/petowners/petcare/caninerespiratory-coronavirus-faq Accessed 10 Apr 2020"

(Extracted from https://www.merck-animal-health-usa.com/condition/canine-coronavirus).

"Are there diseases that can be confused with canine coronavirus?
There are many causes of diarrhea in dogs. Severe cases of coronavirus can be easily confused with parvovirus, and they may occur at the same time. Be sure to see your veterinarian if your dog has diarrhea that does not resolve within twenty- four hours or is associated with significant lethargy or loss of appetite.

Is there any treatment?
There is no specific treatment for canine coronavirus."
(Extracted from https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/coronavirus-disease-in-dogs)

For the safety of the dogs and to stop this outbreak, the track seems to have acted appropriately as this virus could rapidly spread through these canine athletes and could be detrimental to the animals

It is a difficult situation, but it is about the health of the dogs. Hopefully, they will return to health soon and the race can perhaps be reinstated. - Mod.TG

